04154nam a22005295i 9780228004677DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20202020xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280046777 a10.1515/97802280046772doi  a(DE-B1597)657544  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHT169.C32bT67 2020 7aPOL0020002bisacsh04a307.1/2162231 aJoy, Meghan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Right to an Age-Friendly City :bRedistribution, Recognition, and Senior Citizen Rights in Urban Spaces /cMeghan Joy. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Studies in Urban Governance ;v1400tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tA Case Study of Toronto’s Age-Friendly Landscape -- tRedistributing to Senior Citizens: Improving Local Environments through AFCs in Toronto -- tRecognizing Senior Citizens: Promoting a Positive Aging Identity through AFCs in Toronto -- tRights of the City: Empowering Local Policy Actors through AFCs in Toronto -- tConclusion -- tAppendix -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA context of aging populations and urbanization has sparked a global movement to make urban spaces age-friendly. The Age-Friendly City program, developed by the World Health Organization, aims to improve local environments for all population groups, promote a positive aging identity, and empower local policy actors to support senior citizens. Despite growing enthusiasm and policy work by local governments worldwide, considerable gaps remain. These lacunae have led scholars and activists alike to align age-friendly city work with the concept of the right to the city. In The Right to an Age-Friendly City Meghan Joy zeroes in on the intricacies of developing an environment that promotes social and spatial justice for the elderly in Toronto. Weaving together the stories, struggles, and victories of local activists, government staff, and frontline service providers, Joy maps this complex policy area and examines the ways in which age-friendly work successfully enhances senior citizens' access to services and support in the local environment, recognizes the diverse needs of senior citizens in the city, and empowers policy actors from local government and the non-profit sector to support senior citizens. A detailed and timely examination, The Right to an Age-Friendly City offers both broad and tangible insights into the intermingled political, economic, cultural, and administrative changes needed to protect the rights of senior citizens to access urban space in Toronto and beyond.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCity planningxSocial aspectszOntariozToronto. 0aPopulation agingxSocial aspectszOntariozToronto. 0aUrban older peoplexCivil rightszOntariozToronto. 0aUrban older peoplexServices forzOntariozToronto. 0aUrban older peoplezOntariozTorontoxSocial conditions. 0aUrban policyzOntariozToronto. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / City Planning & Urban Development.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780228004677?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228004677423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228004677/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles